1. What is SQL?
SQL (Structured Query Language) is a standard language used to communicate with relational databases. It is used to perform operations such as storing, retrieving, updating, and deleting data.
SQL allows us to manage structured data in a tabular format using queries. It is widely used in database systems like MySQL, Oracle, SQL Server, and PostgreSQL.

2. Difference between sql and MySQL
Feature 	SQL (Structured Query Language)	MySQL (Relational Database System)
Type	Programming Language	RDBMS Software
Primary Use	Managing and querying data	Storing and organizing data
Updates	Syntax remains relatively static	Frequent software updates and versions
Portability	Can be used in many database systems	A specific product used to run queries
User Interface	No graphical interface	Supports GUIs like MySQL Workbench
